      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Melvin Calvin, who won the 1961 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for research on the assimilation of carbon dioxide in plants, has suggested that a large part of the oil shortage foreseen for the United States (front page, Feb. 17) could be averted by growing plants that produce a fluid similar to oil, from which chemicals and fuel could be made on our surplus farm and ranch land.</p>
        <p>Dr. Calvin has in little more than a decade increased production from 7 barrels an acre to 12 barrels an acre and has brought the cost down from $80 a barrel to $30 a barrel with very little funding from the Government.</p>
        <p>The potential exists for the United States to be completely oil independent by this biomass means, and also to be one of the world's major exporters of liquid fuels. SIDNEY HARRIS  Alexandria, Va., Feb. 19, 1987  WHAT WE CAN DO TO LIMIT OUR OIL DEPENDENCY</p>
      </block>
